  <h1>Extended Biography</h1>
  
  <p><strong>Colt Camron Lien</strong> is the Director of Choral Activities and an Assistant Professor at the University of Arkansas at Monticello. A dynamic conductor and educator, he is known as a dedicated program builder who fosters exceptional growth and high-level artistry. He designs his concerts to be authentic musical experiences, thoughtfully programmed to explore diverse cultures and convey compelling human messages.</p>
  
  <p>As the founder of the Runestone Chorale, Lien built a 50-voice community ensemble that, in its inaugural season, performed Dvorak's <em>Te Deum</em> with the Central Lakes Symphony Orchestra of Minnesota. He brings this same focus on growth and community engagement from his previous positions as a high school and church choir director.</p>

  <p>Beyond the podium, his work encompasses a broad polymathic scope across theoretical physics, computer science, and archaeoacoustics. He is the author of the Fluid-Resonance Torus Framework—a manuscript submitted to <em>Foundations of Physics</em> that models the universe as a continuous superfluid governed by harmonic resonance. His computer science research involves bare-metal systems development in Rust, having engineered TorusOS and achieved a verified EEMBC CoreMark score outperforming existing systems, alongside ongoing work in quantum transpiler benchmarking. Additionally, he actively researches the resonant properties of ancient lithic structures, analyzing the intersection of acoustic phenomena and human history.</p>
  
  <p>Lien holds a Master of Music in Choral Conducting from Michigan State University and a Bachelor of Music in Music Education from Concordia College. His mentors include internationally recognized conductor-educators Sandra Snow, Derrick Fox, David Rayl, Jonathan Reed, René Clausen, and Michael Culloton.</p>
</BaseLayout>